blocks.content: Define the dimension of a vector space as the cardinality of its bases. Note that by ~ lvecdim , all bases are equinumerous. (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 6-May-2023.)

blocks.name: dimval
blocks.content: The dimension of a vector space ` F ` is the cardinality of one of its bases. (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 6-May-2023.)

thm dimval(class c0, class c1, class c2) {

  syl(wcel(c0, clvec), wceq(cfv(cldim, c0), cuni(cima(chash, c2))), wcel(c0, universe))

  uniex(cima(chash, c2))

  funimaex(chash, c2)
  fvexi(c2, clbs, c0)
  unieqd(cima(chash, c2), csn(cfv(chash, c1)), wa(wcel(c0, clvec), wcel(c1, c2)))
  mpbird(wa(wcel(c0, clvec), wcel(c1, c2)), wceq(cima(chash, c2), csn(cfv(chash, c1))), wral(hs1, cima(chash, c2), wceq(cv(hs1), cfv(chash, c1))))

  eqtr2d(cv(hs1), cfv(chash, c1), cfv(chash, cv(hs2)), wa(wa(wa(wa(wcel(c0, clvec), wcel(c1, c2)), wcel(cv(hs1), cima(chash, c2))), wcel(cv(hs2), c2)), wceq(cfv(chash, cv(hs2)), cv(hs1))))
  adantr(wa(wa(wa(wcel(c0, clvec), wcel(c1, c2)), wcel(cv(hs1), cima(chash, c2))), wcel(cv(hs2), c2)), wceq(cfv(chash, cv(hs2)), cv(hs1)), wceq(cfv(chash, c1), cfv(chash, cv(hs2))))
  syl(wa(wa(wa(wcel(c0, clvec), wcel(c1, c2)), wcel(cv(hs1), cima(chash, c2))), wcel(cv(hs2), c2)), wceq(cfv(chash, c1), cfv(chash, cv(hs2))), wbr(c1, cen, cv(hs2)))
  ad4ant124(wcel(c0, clvec), wcel(c1, c2), wcel(cv(hs1), cima(chash, c2)), wcel(cv(hs2), c2), wbr(c1, cen, cv(hs2)))
  lvecdim(c0, c1, c2, cv(hs2))
  hasheni(c1, cv(hs2))
  simpr(wa(wa(wa(wcel(c0, clvec), wcel(c1, c2)), wcel(cv(hs1), cima(chash, c2))), wcel(cv(hs2), c2)), wceq(cfv(chash, cv(hs2)), cv(hs1)))
  adantl(wa(wcel(c0, clvec), wcel(c1, c2)), wcel(cv(hs1), cima(chash, c2)), wrex(hs2, c2, wceq(cfv(chash, cv(hs2)), cv(hs1))))
  mpan(wcel(cv(hs1), cima(chash, c2)), wrex(hs2, c2, wceq(cfv(chash, cv(hs2)), cv(hs1))), wfun(chash))
  ax-mp(wfun(chash), wf(chash, universe, cun(cn0, csn(cpnf))))
  ffun(chash, universe, cun(cn0, csn(cpnf)))

  ne0i(c1, c2)
  necon3bii(cima(chash, c2), emptycls, c2, emptycls)
  mp2an(wb(wceq(cima(chash, c2), emptycls), wceq(c2, emptycls)), wfn(chash, universe), wss(c2, universe))

  unisn(cfv(chash, c1))
  fvex(chash, c1)
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
  diff.hs0.c(universe)

  diff.hs2.w(wceq(cv(hs1), cfv(chash, c1)))
  diff.hs2.c(chash)
  diff.hs2.c(cv(hs1))
  diff.hs2.c(c2)
  diff.hs1.c(cima(chash, c2))
  diff.hs1.c(cfv(chash, c1))
}

  ‚ä£ c2 =(LBasis ` c0)
} = {
  3eqtrd((dim ` c0), (# ` c1), ‚ãÉ(# " c2), ‚ãÉ {(# ` c1)}, (c0 ‚àà LVec ‚àß c1 ‚àà c2))

  syl(c0 ‚àà LVec, (dim ` c0)= ‚ãÉ(# " c2), c0 ‚àà ùïå)
  elex(c0, clvec)
  fvmpt(hs0, c0, universe, cldim, ‚ãÉ(# " c2), ‚ãÉ(# "(LBasis ` hs0)))
  unieqd((# "(LBasis ` hs0)), (# " c2), hs0 = c0)
  imaeq2d(chash, (LBasis ` hs0), c2, hs0 = c0)
  syl6eqr((LBasis ` hs0), c2, (LBasis ` c0), hs0 = c0)
  fveq2(hs0, c0, clbs)
  df-dim(hs0)
  uniex((# " c2))
  mp2b((# " c2)‚àà ùïå, (# : ùïå ‚Üí(‚Ñï0 ‚ãÉ { +‚àû })), Fun(#))
  funimaex(chash, c2)
  fvexi(c2, clbs, c0)
  unieqd((# " c2), {(# ` c1)}, (c0 ‚àà LVec ‚àß c1 ‚àà c2))
  mpbird((c0 ‚àà LVec ‚àß c1 ‚àà c2), (# " c2)= {(# ` c1)}, ‚àÄ(hs1 ‚àà(# " c2), hs1 =(# ` c1)))
  ralrimiva(hs1, (# " c2), (c0 ‚àà LVec ‚àß c1 ‚àà c2), hs1 =(# ` c1))
  r19.29a(hs2, c2, ((c0 ‚àà LVec ‚àß c1 ‚àà c2)‚àß hs1 ‚àà(# " c2)), hs1 =(# ` c1), (# ` hs2)= hs1)
  eqtr2d(hs1, (# ` c1), (# ` hs2), ((((c0 ‚àà LVec ‚àß c1 ‚àà c2)‚àß hs1 ‚àà(# " c2))‚àß hs2 ‚àà c2)‚àß(# ` hs2)= hs1))
  adantr((((c0 ‚àà LVec ‚àß c1 ‚àà c2)‚àß hs1 ‚àà(# " c2))‚àß hs2 ‚àà c2), (# ` hs2)= hs1, (# ` c1)=(# ` hs2))
  syl((((c0 ‚àà LVec ‚àß c1 ‚àà c2)‚àß hs1 ‚àà(# " c2))‚àß hs2 ‚àà c2), (# ` c1)=(# ` hs2), c1[‚âÖ]hs2)
  ad4ant124(c0 ‚àà LVec, c1 ‚àà c2, hs1 ‚àà(# " c2), hs2 ‚àà c2, c1[‚âÖ]hs2)
  lvecdim(c0, c1, c2, hs2)
  hasheni(c1, hs2)
  simpr((((c0 ‚àà LVec ‚àß c1 ‚àà c2)‚àß hs1 ‚àà(# " c2))‚àß hs2 ‚àà c2), (# ` hs2)= hs1)
  adantl((c0 ‚àà LVec ‚àß c1 ‚àà c2), hs1 ‚àà(# " c2), ‚àÉ(hs2 ‚àà c2,(# ` hs2)= hs1))
  mpan(hs1 ‚àà(# " c2), ‚àÉ(hs2 ‚àà c2,(# ` hs2)= hs1), Fun(#))
  ax-mp(Fun(#), (# : ùïå ‚Üí(‚Ñï0 ‚ãÉ { +‚àû })))
  ffun(chash, universe, (‚Ñï0 ‚ãÉ { +‚àû }))
  fvelima(hs2, chash, hs1, c2)
  syl((c0 ‚àà LVec ‚àß c1 ‚àà c2), ((# " c2)= {(# ` c1)} ‚Üî ‚àÄ(hs1 ‚àà(# " c2), hs1 =(# ` c1))), (# " c2)‚â† ‚àÖ)
  sylibr((c0 ‚àà LVec ‚àß c1 ‚àà c2), (# " c2)‚â† ‚àÖ, c2 ‚â† ‚àÖ)
  adantl(c0 ‚àà LVec, c1 ‚àà c2, c2 ‚â† ‚àÖ)

  necon3bii((# " c2), emptycls, c2, emptycls)

blocks.name: dimvalfi
blocks.content: The dimension of a vector space ` F ` is the cardinality of one of its bases. This version of ~ dimval does not depend on the axiom of choice, but it is limited to the case where the base ` S ` is finite. (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 24-May-2023.)

  adantr(wa(wa(w3a(wcel(c0, clvec), wcel(c1, c2), wcel(c1, cfn)), wcel(cv(hs1), cima(chash, c2))), wcel(cv(hs2), c2)), wceq(cfv(chash, cv(hs2)), cv(hs1)), wceq(cfv(chash, c1), cfv(chash, cv(hs2))))

  lvecdimfi(c1, cv(hs2), c2, c0, wa(wa(w3a(wcel(c0, clvec), wcel(c1, c2), wcel(c1, cfn)), wcel(cv(hs1), cima(chash, c2))), wcel(cv(hs2), c2)))

  sylibr(w3a(wcel(c0, clvec), wcel(c1, c2), wcel(c1, cfn)), wne(cima(chash, c2), emptycls), wne(c2, emptycls))
  3ad2ant2(wcel(c0, clvec), wcel(c1, c2), wcel(c1, cfn), wne(c2, emptycls))
  ne0i(c1, c2)

blocks.content: A nonzero vector ` X ` is a basis of a line spanned by the singleton ` X ` . Spans of nonzero singletons are sometimes called "atoms", see ~ df-lsatoms and for example ~ lsatlspsn . (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 20-May-2023.)

blocks.name: lindsun
blocks.content: Condition for the union of two independent sets to be an independent set. (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 9-May-2023.)

  syl12anc(w0, wcel(cun(c0, c1), cfv(clinds, c2)), wcel(c2, clmod), wss(cun(c0, c1), cfv(cbs, c2)), wral(hs1, cun(c0, c1), wral(hs0, cdif(cfv(cbs, cfv(csca, c2)), csn(cfv(c0g, cfv(csca, c2)))), wn(wcel(co(cv(hs0), cfv(cvsca, c2), cv(hs1)), cfv(c3, cdif(cun(c0, c1), csn(cv(hs1)))))))))

blocks.name: dimkerim
blocks.content: Given a linear map ` F ` between vector spaces ` V ` and ` U ` , the dimension of the vector space ` V ` is the sum of the dimension of ` F ` 's kernel and the dimension of ` F ` 's image. Second part of theorem 5.3 in [Lang] p. 141 This can also be described as the Rank-nullity theorem, ` ( dim `` I ) ` being the rank of ` F ` (the dimension of its image), and ` ( dim `` K ) ` its nullity (the dimension of its kernel). (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 17-May-2023.)

blocks.name: qusdimsum

blocks.name: fedgmul
blocks.content: The multiplicativity formula for degrees of field extensions. Given ` E ` a field extension of ` F ` , itself a field extension of ` K ` , we have ` [ E : K ] = [ E : F ] [ F : K ] ` . Proposition 1.2 of [Lang], p. 224. Here ` ( dim `` A ) ` is the degree of the extension ` E ` of ` K ` , ` ( dim `` B ) ` is the degree of the extension ` E ` of ` F ` , and ` ( dim `` C ) ` is the degree of the extension ` F ` of ` K ` . This proof is valid for infinite dimensions, and is actually valid for division ring extensions, not just field extensions. (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 25-Jul-2023.)
